> Sicily, 'The Old Country', is the birthplace of Vito Corleone and home to one of our favourite Italian dishes: Caponata. Patrick learned how to make this dish whilst filming in the beautiful coastal town of Catania and (in a fairly risky move) has decided to recreate it with a few of his own flavours. Italians are fiercely protective of their recipes so, for his sake, let's keep this one under our hats!

Pre-heat the #oven{} to 220 degrees. Slice the @aubergine{1} in half lengthways and then slice each half into 5 strips. Dice the aubergine into 2cm cubes, finely chop the @celery stick{⅗} and one clove of @garlic{2%cloves}. Remove the core from the @red pepper{1} and @green pepper{1} and chop into little bite-sized chunks.

In a #bowl{}, coat the aubergine and peppers in 1 tbsp of @olive oil{}. Spread evenly on a #baking tray{} and roast on the top shelf of the oven. Cook for ~{20%minutes} or until a little crispy around the edges.

Heat 2 tsp of olive oil in a large #frying pan{} on medium heat. Once hot, add in the garlic and celery with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{}. While they cook, slice open the @sausage{1} and put the meat in the pan too. Break it up and cook for ~{5%minutes}.

Tip in the tin of @chopped tomatoes{1%tin} and then refill the tin by a fifth with water. Swill the water around and add this into the sauce. Add @salt{¼%tsp}, @sugar{1%tsp}, the @capers{½%tbsp} and @white wine vinegar{1%tbsp}. Leave to simmer and thicken up for ~{10-15%minutes}.

Once the vegetables have roasted, remove from the oven. Switch off the oven and turn the grill to high. Add the roasted vegetables into the pan and stir.

Cut the @ciabatta{1} and toast on each side under the grill. Once toasted, cut the remaining clove of garlic in half. Rub the clove of garlic across the top of the ciabatta. Drizzle over a little olive oil and a pinch of salt.

Once the caponata has thickened up nicely, serve into warm #bowls{}. It can be eaten with cutlery or by using the ciabatta as a small edible shovel!